    think='Let me now check a few more critical things before writing the review
:\n\n1. The `DesignTokens.secondaryColor` usage - the design doc says legacy ali
ases should not be used\n2. Whether the `matching.service.ts` transaction proper
ly handles the `matches` unique constraint\n3. Whether `checkAndCreateMutualMatc
h` properly queries for existing match within the same transaction after duplica
te error\n4. The `app.config.ts` for clientUrl used in MatchingGateway\n5. Wheth
er `matching.module.ts` needs `ConversationEntity` and `ConversationParticipantE
ntity` in TypeOrm imports (since MatchingService uses them via DataSource, not v
ia Repository)\n6. Check if there\'s any issue with `matching.gateway.ts` import
ing `appConfig` at module level\n\nLet me also check the `matching.service.ts` m
ore carefully for a potential bug: when `checkAndCreateMutualMatch` catches a du
plicate error, it calls `manager.findOne` but doesn\'t pass the entity class as 
first argument properly? Let me check:\n```typescript\nconst existing = await ma
nager.findOne(MatchEntity, {\n  where: { user_a_id: userA, user_b_id: userB },\n
});\n```\nActually, in TypeORM 0.3+, `manager.findOne` takes the entity class as
first arg and options as second. This looks correct.\n\nWait, I see an issue! In
`matching.service.ts`:\n```typescript\nconst conversation = await this.dataSourc
e\n  .getRepository(ConversationEntity)\n  .find({\n    where: matchIds.map((id)
=> ({ match_id: id })),\n  });\n```\nThis creates an OR condition across all mat
ch IDs, which is correct.\n\nAnother potential issue: In `matching.service.ts` `
getRecommendations`, when cache hit occurs:\n```typescript\nconst parsed = JSON.
parse(cached) as CachedRecommendation[];\nconst userIds = parsed.map((p) => p.us
er_id);\nreturn this.buildRecommendations(userIds, userId);\n```\nBut `buildReco
mmendations` queries profiles using `findByIds`. The problem is that `findByIds`
doesn\'t guarantee order! So the cached order (by score) might be lost. This is 
a **functional issue** because the PRD says "cards should be sorted by composite
score". On cache hit, the order might be randomized by `findByIds`.\n\nWait, let
me check `buildRecommendations`:\n```typescript\nconst profiles = await this.pro
fileRepo.findByIds(userIds);\nconst profileMap = new Map(profiles.map((p) => [p.
user_id, p]));\n\nreturn userIds\n  .map((id) => {\n    const p = profileMap.get
(id);\n    ...\n  })\n  .filter(...)\n```\nAh! It does map over `userIds` first,
then looks up in `profileMap`. So the order IS preserved from `userIds`. That\'s
correct. Good.\n\nLet me check another issue: `matching.service.ts` uses `calcul
ateAge` from `../../common/utils/age-calculator`. Let me verify this exists and 
handles UTC correctly as the PRD requires.\n\nActually, I should check the `quer
yCandidatesFromDb` SQL more carefully. The PRD says:\n- `last_active_at` for act
ivity scoring. But the SQL uses `last_login_at`. Are these the same column? The 
`users` entity might have `last_login_at` but the PRD says `last_active_at`. Thi
s could be a discrepancy.\n\nLet me check the UserEntity to see what columns exi
st.\n\nAlso, the PRD mentions profile completeness guard should block matching-r
elated requests with code 1000. The controller has `@UseGuards(JwtAuthGuard, Pro
fileCompletionGuard)` on all three endpoints. Good.\n\nAnother issue: In `home_p
age.dart`, the `GestureDetector` for swipe card uses `onHorizontalDragUpdate` an
d `onHorizontalDragEnd`. These are fine for manual swiping. But Maestro can\'t e
asily simulate drag gestures. However, the action buttons provide an alternative
path, and the Maestro flow does use `swipe` command with `optional: true`. The `
swipe` command in Maestro should work for this.\n\nWait, looking at the Maestro 
flow:\n```yaml\n- swipe:\n    direction: LEFT\n    optional: true\n```\nMaestro\
's `swipe` command works on the whole screen. It should trigger the Flutter gest
ure detector. So this is probably fine.\n\nLet me check one more thing - the `Ma
tchingSocketClient` in `home_page.dart` is created in `initState` and only if `a
uthState is AuthAuthenticated`. What if the user is on the home page but auth st
ate isn\'t loaded yet? This could be a race condition. The `initState` runs once
when the widget is first created. If the auth bloc hasn\'t emitted `AuthAuthenti
cated` yet, the socket won\'t be initialized.\n\nActually, looking at the flow: 
after login, the app navigates to `/home`. At that point, the auth bloc should a
lready be authenticated. But if the app is opened with an existing token, the au
th bloc might still be loading. In that case, the socket won\'t connect. This is
a potential issue.\n\nLet me also check if `home_page.dart` listens to auth stat
e changes to reconnect the socket when auth becomes available. It doesn\'t. This
is a **Major** issue because if the user opens the app and the auth state is sti
ll loading when HomePage is built, the socket will never connect.\n\nActually, l
et me think about this more carefully. The `MainPage` is created when navigating
to `/home`. The `AuthBloc` is likely a global bloc provided at the app level. Wh
en the app starts, it checks the token. If valid, it emits `AuthAuthenticated`. 
But the timing could be:\n1. App starts → AuthBloc starts checking token\n2. Rou
ter sees auth state → navigates to `/home`\n3. HomePage initState runs → reads A
uthBloc state\n\nIf the router waits for auth state before navigating, then by t
he time HomePage is built, auth should be authenticated. But if there\'s a race 
condition where HomePage builds before auth state is ready, the socket won\'t in
itialize.\n\nThis is somewhat mitigated by the fact that `context.read<AuthBloc>
().state` is called synchronously in `initState`. If the auth bloc has already e
mitted the state, it will work. But there\'s no `BlocListener` to react to later
auth state changes.\n\nI think this is a valid concern but not necessarily block
ing. Let me mark it as Major.\n\nLet me now check the `DesignTokens.secondaryCol
or` issue and the `withOpacity` deprecation.\n\nActually, `withOpacity` was depr
ecated in Flutter 3.27.0, but this project uses `sdk: \'>=3.4.0 <4.0.0\'`. The F
lutter SDK version 3.4.0 corresponds to Dart 3.4.0, which is Flutter 3.22.0. At 
that version, `withOpacity` is NOT deprecated. So this is not an issue for this 
project.\n\nBut `DesignTokens.secondaryColor` - the design doc says:\n> **Legacy
aliases**: `tokens.dart` 中的别名，如 `surfaceColor = background` — **禁止在新代
码中使用**。\n\nLet me check if `secondaryColor` is a legacy alias.',
